Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Services
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Holds an `HttpClient` and shared state (cache, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps state consistent app-wide. |
| `MainViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation creates a fresh VM with fresh state — no stale data when the user returns to a page. |
| `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Same reasoning — a new instance per navigation ensures the detail data matches the selected item. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Pages pair 1:1 with their VM. Transient ensures each navigation gets a clean page + VM pair, avoiding UI state leaks. |

**Key rule of thumb:**
- **Singleton** → shared, stateless-ish infrastructure (HTTP clients, caches, settings).
- **Transient** → anything with per-screen state (pages, ViewModels).
- **Scoped** → rarely used in MAUI (no built-in scope-per-navigation), but useful if you create manual scopes.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **transient** or **scoped** service into a **singleton** — the shorter-lived service becomes a captive dependency and effectively lives forever.
